{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"09c0f629-5fe3-46c2-b218-0940b11aaba2","content":"For NativeAOT apps, the runtime doesn't bundle `createdump`, so you must explicitly point to it. Here are the pod spec changes:\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: your-app\n      env:\n        # Enable automatic mini dump on crash\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n          value: \"1\"\n        # Dump type: 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n          value: \"4\"\n        # Path to createdump (required for NativeAOT — it's not bundled)\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n          value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"\n        # Dump output path with PID placeholder\n        - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n          value: \"/tmp/dumps/coredump.%d\"\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: crash-dumps\n          mountPath: /tmp/dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: crash-dumps\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 2Gi\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`** — critical for NativeAOT since the runtime doesn't ship with `createdump`.\n- **`%d`** in the dump name expands to the PID, preventing overwrites.\n- **Dump type 4 (Full)** gives you the most data; use `1` (Mini) or `3` (Triage) if space is tight.\n- The `emptyDir` volume is ephemeral — swap it for a **PersistentVolumeClaim** if you need dumps to survive pod restarts.\n- Make sure `/opt/tools/createdump` is executable and built for the same architecture as your container image.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b40a3309-0385-41e2-aa08-740a7443ee09","outputTokens":458,"requestId":"980F:3387D:541EBE5:5CB0FE7:69F406B9"},"id":"720eb20c-0753-4284-8f4e-e18c71b37973","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:49:58.556Z","parentId":"46086bde-cbaa-46ac-b150-e74247db9676"}
